    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Missile Defense System Ignores Terrorist Threat</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Jon Gellman letter comments on July 15 article on fusion research; contends that likelihood that Government's research on laser fusion will lead to development of new generation of suitcase-size hydrogen bombs is remote</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Fusion-Research Effort Draws Fire'' (news article, July 15): The likelihood that the Government's research on laser fusion will lead to the development of a new generation of suitcase-size hydrogen bombs is remote. What it may lead to is commercial fusion power that could end our dependence on fossil fuels and dirty fission plants.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Fusion-Research Effort Draws Fire'' (news article, July 15): The likelihood that the Government's research on laser fusion will lead to the development of a new generation of suitcase-size hydrogen bombs is remote. What it may lead to is commercial fusion power that could end our dependence on fossil fuels and dirty fission plants.</p>
        <p>If fusion power were perfected, carbon dioxide, dams, strip mines, acid rain, smog and oil spills could be avoided.</p>
        <p>JON GELLMAN  Jersey City, July 15, 1998</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
